webwork.pg-code:
Context(Point)->flags->set( reduceConstants => 0, reduceConstantFunctions => 0,  );
Context()->variables->add(y=>"Real");
$f = Formula("x^2/(5/2)^2 + y^2/5^2");
$vertices = Formula("(-5/2,0), (5/2,0)");
$my_evaluator = $vertices -> cmp(
 showHints=>1,
 showLengthHints => 1,
 partialCredit => 1,
); 
$l1 = Formula("2x");
$l2 = Formula("-2x");
    $multians = MultiAnswer($l1,$l2)->with(
      singleResult => 1,
      checker => sub {
          my ( $correct, $student, $self ) = @_;
          my ( $f1stu, $f2stu ) = @{$student};
          my ( $f1, $f2 ) = @{$correct};
          return ( ($f1 == $f1stu && $f2 == $f2stu) ||
               ($f1 == $f2stu && $f2 == $f1stu)  
          );
      }
    );

sidebyside.p:
We substitute in the given equation.
4y^2 - (2)^2 \amp = 16 4y^2 \amp = 20 y^2 \amp = 5 y \amp = \pm \sqrt{5}
There are two points with x=2, namely \left(2, \sqrt{5}\right) and \left(2, -\sqrt{5}\right), as shown in the figure.

